1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:27,658
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:28,228 --> 00:00:35,136
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:35,155 --> 00:00:48,448
So we were going through the Kanda, which is these five heaps that the Buddha talks about, these five aggregates in which he deconstructs the psychophysical organism.

4
00:00:50,009 --> 00:00:54,674
And today we'll do the word Rupa.

5
00:00:54,959 --> 00:01:00,365
So Rupa translates as corporeality, or your body, basically, your body.

6
00:01:02,106 --> 00:01:06,891
And the first question that you have to ask yourself is, what do we actually know?

7
00:01:08,412 --> 00:01:15,120
What do we actually know in terms of direct experience of the body itself, save through the senses?

8
00:01:18,483 --> 00:01:23,227
So if you take just a simple example like your toenails, because every so often you cut them off.

9
00:01:24,472 --> 00:01:25,634
What do you know about your toenails?

10
00:01:26,314 --> 00:01:30,960
You know how they look, you know how they feel, hard and all that.

11
00:01:30,980 --> 00:01:32,662
But you don't know what it is to be a toenail.

12
00:01:35,486 --> 00:01:45,039
If there were nerves within your toenail, can you imagine the agony of having to cut them off every so often?

13
00:01:45,058 --> 00:01:46,140
The same with your hair.

14
00:01:49,004 --> 00:01:51,527
So, our

15
00:01:53,126 --> 00:01:58,352
direct experience of the body is still dependent on these outer senses.

16
00:01:59,772 --> 00:02:02,796
If there's no nerve senses, there's no nerves there, we don't know what it is.

17
00:02:03,876 --> 00:02:06,338
And we don't even know the inside of things.

18
00:02:07,819 --> 00:02:15,907
We don't know what, you know, what makes a nail or what makes your hair.

19
00:02:15,926 --> 00:02:19,510
I mean, we know scientifically, but we don't know by direct experience.

20
00:02:19,550 --> 00:02:21,092
So we know, for instance,

21
00:02:21,729 --> 00:02:32,003
by science tells us that every time we breathe there's this exchange of carbon dioxide for oxygen but you don't know it, at least I don't know anyway, I should talk to myself.

22
00:02:34,026 --> 00:02:43,079
I've never, I don't know oxygen, I mean I'm told it's there and I'd die without it but I haven't a clue, I've never experienced it as a direct experience.

23
00:02:43,979 --> 00:02:44,480
So

24
00:02:45,962 --> 00:02:52,770
When it comes to understanding what the Buddha means by the body, he's not talking about the physicality of the body.

25
00:02:53,251 --> 00:02:59,979
This is the point, he's talking about how we experience the body, the direct experience of the body.

26
00:03:00,579 --> 00:03:09,650
And what it comes down to is the four basic elements, the Mahabhuta, the four basic elements.

27
00:03:09,669 --> 00:03:14,534
And they're described in a metaphorical way, the earth, fire, water and air.

28
00:03:15,680 --> 00:03:40,067
now earth are those feelings that we experience as pressure, heaviness, light, you know that sort of sensation the fire is heat, it also includes cold of course, the whole gamut of temperature water is cohesive, elasticity, what joins things and air is movement

29
00:03:42,241 --> 00:04:10,155
and what the Buddha is saying and this is fairly straightforward in the ancient world it would seem if you go into a sensation deep enough you'll be able to describe it in those sorts of ways now don't confuse this with the four, I don't know what they call them now, the four in science the four great forces

30
00:04:10,455 --> 00:04:14,540
electromagnetism, gravity, strong and weak force.

31
00:04:15,301 --> 00:04:15,562
Isn't it?

32
00:04:16,202 --> 00:04:16,923
What do they call those?

33
00:04:16,944 --> 00:04:17,545
The four what?

34
00:04:18,406 --> 00:04:19,326
I've been trying to find out.

35
00:04:20,507 --> 00:04:21,970
Well, those are completely different, you see.

36
00:04:22,511 --> 00:04:27,237
What science is describing is matter, as it were, the laws of matter, etc., in itself.

37
00:04:29,119 --> 00:04:32,362
I mean, we experience gravity, I suppose, in terms of weight.

38
00:04:35,194 --> 00:05:04,154
but the others don't seem to fit so what the Buddha's talking about when he talks about the four great elements is how we experience matter not that matter is like that in itself it's just the way the mind experiences matter so there's two things isn't there there's matter in itself and there's matter how mind experiences matter

39
00:05:05,350 --> 00:05:31,846
so that's what he's talking about and then from there I'll just mention them quickly because there's no real time to go into it there arises the derivatives so that's from that you get your seeing hearing, smelling, tasting touching and then there are further ones that are put as femininity or virility

40
00:05:32,300 --> 00:05:34,562
physical base of mind, which is the brain.

41
00:05:35,704 --> 00:05:38,168
Actually, I won't go into that just yet.

42
00:05:39,509 --> 00:05:43,415
Then there's bodily, verbal expression, so that's the body.

43
00:05:44,016 --> 00:05:49,723
These are all secondary to this original contact that the mind has with the body.

44
00:05:50,886 --> 00:05:55,932
The physical life itself, so we know that the body has its own sort of energy, its own force.

45
00:05:57,875 --> 00:06:01,259
Each cell has its own little life, you might say.

46
00:06:02,708 --> 00:06:07,355
And there's a space element, that's part of it, there's holes in the body.

47
00:06:10,379 --> 00:06:15,987
And then there's physical agility, elasticity, adaptability, growth, continuity.

48
00:06:17,310 --> 00:06:24,740
There's decay, there's impermanence, and finally there's those things that are nutrients to the body.

49
00:06:25,362 --> 00:06:27,024
All that is sort of secondary.

50
00:06:27,685 --> 00:06:29,728
What we're interested in, in terms of

51
00:06:30,923 --> 00:06:54,365
the process of awakening is the fact that although we experience the body as a whole, as an entire, as an experience when you go into it, it's made up of all these little bits and pieces and therefore it loses that substantiality it feels substantial if you fall over on a mountain and bang your head on the floor

52
00:06:55,612 --> 00:07:02,523
But in fact, it's just feeling, different types of feelings that arise.

53
00:07:03,524 --> 00:07:12,317
At a physical level, it's just a bunch of subatomic particles touching another bunch of stuff.

54
00:07:12,338 --> 00:07:19,088
But in terms of our normal reality, it's a person who's hit his head on the floor and is hurt.

55
00:07:27,269 --> 00:07:41,228
So this is part of the Buddhist strategy of undermining this mistake, this delusion, this belief that I am the body, by knowing what you're not.

56
00:07:43,271 --> 00:07:47,656
It's by realizing what you're not that you begin to realize what you are.

57
00:07:49,257 --> 00:07:51,379
So that's his methodology, you see.

58
00:07:51,880 --> 00:07:56,927
He's not turning us around to look at something which is the unconditioned or nirvana.

59
00:07:57,728 --> 00:08:00,793
He says that will arise naturally when you realize what you're not.

60
00:08:04,377 --> 00:08:08,343
So let me leave you with one or two exercises that you can do sometimes.

61
00:08:10,047 --> 00:08:11,428
So we did the standing, you see.

62
00:08:11,709 --> 00:08:13,992
So even there, just that very simple thing.

63
00:08:14,031 --> 00:08:16,716
Normally speaking, there's just the feeling of standing.

64
00:08:17,759 --> 00:08:26,569
But when we go into those feelings in the feet, we find actually, you know, we can distinguish this heat from the pressure.

65
00:08:26,589 --> 00:08:35,561
At one level it's just feeling of standing, and at a different level we see it's made up of all these bits and pieces.

66
00:08:35,581 --> 00:08:40,947
When you get pain, you see, you might have pain, you might have a sharp pain, from say the sitting.

67
00:08:41,788 --> 00:09:08,471
or a headache when you go into it when you stop using the word headache or pain and you go in to describe the sensations that are there you are using different words you might use heat or pressure tightness or something else the word pain disappears also you know how do we know the difference between the touch of metal and the touch of wood

68
00:09:09,346 --> 00:09:15,517
If you go into that touch, you'll be able to discern what it is that's actually different at that feeling level.

69
00:09:17,399 --> 00:09:23,390
People, of course, who, you know, these wine tasters and tea tasters, they do that, don't they?

70
00:09:23,951 --> 00:09:32,687
They get very into the distinctly different little bits that go into making this fullness of taste.

71
00:09:35,148 --> 00:09:37,471
At a more subtle level, it's the eyes.

72
00:09:37,490 --> 00:09:40,434
The eyes are the heat element, fire.

73
00:09:42,937 --> 00:09:55,854
And in a moment of sparky meditation, you might actually experience what is happening in the mind when it takes in the stuff from the eyes.

74
00:09:56,375 --> 00:09:59,197
And it's actually imaging it as little flames.

75
00:10:00,663 --> 00:10:07,472
It's the same with hearing, when you actually put your attention on the ear drum, on the actual hear, the process of hearing.

76
00:10:08,394 --> 00:10:11,759
And you can get right down to that basis of that first impact.

77
00:10:12,379 --> 00:10:15,224
All that is, is the touch of the air wave on the ear drum.

78
00:10:16,365 --> 00:10:19,649
Which is then taken inward as it were to the next perception.

79
00:10:20,710 --> 00:10:24,754
You see it drawn into the mind until it actually takes on the sound of a bell.

80
00:10:25,114 --> 00:10:28,917
But that's not what's actually at that base.

81
00:10:28,937 --> 00:10:29,998
It's just contact.

82
00:10:30,018 --> 00:10:35,783
It's just pressure.

83
00:10:35,844 --> 00:10:40,947
So that's what the Buddha means when he's talking about rupa, about corporeality.

84
00:10:42,730 --> 00:10:50,397
You may also, just as an aside, come across another meaning when you're reading, and that is the subtle

85
00:10:51,524 --> 00:10:59,336
the subtle material that's within the mind itself that creates images.

86
00:11:00,899 --> 00:11:10,697
And through meditation, through concentration meditation, these become very bright, very obvious images in the mind, like a light.

87
00:11:12,482 --> 00:11:22,817
And these sort of nimitta, as they're called, are then used for these absorption meditations to create an inner sense of bliss.

88
00:11:22,836 --> 00:11:25,720
So those also are known as rupa.

89
00:11:30,346 --> 00:11:38,236
And so taking that as a basis for those types of mental states that we call the absorptions,

90
00:11:39,365 --> 00:11:42,288
There's a further stage when even that image disappears.

91
00:11:43,828 --> 00:11:48,813
And they're known as the Arupa, the no-image state.

92
00:11:48,833 --> 00:11:51,897
So there's the fullness, really, of this word Rupa.

93
00:11:53,119 --> 00:11:57,123
And often you'll hear a Buddha Rupa, so it's the Buddha statue.

94
00:11:57,383 --> 00:11:58,884
So it's used in that sense too.

95
00:12:00,966 --> 00:12:04,629
With Easterners, that's a normal way of referring to a statue, a Rupa.

96
00:12:07,461 --> 00:12:22,778
But the main thing is to, in your meditation, occasionally when you feel nicely concentrated, nicely sort of investigative, curious, is to go into a sensation and begin to deconstruct it.

97
00:12:25,280 --> 00:12:34,710
And that's one of the purposes why the Buddha points out these different elements, these different four elements.

98
00:12:36,211 --> 00:12:36,371
Yeah?

99
00:12:48,907 --> 00:12:52,658
I can only hope my words are clarified not modified.

100
00:12:54,062 --> 00:13:03,490
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

